Intermediate R

The goal of this workshop is to build on R fundamentals we began in the Introduction to R class. In that class we learned how to read and write files, what objects, are, tidy data (long vs. wide form objects), and how to transform data objects using dplyr commands. This workshop will briefly review those topics and build upon them by introducing object filtering, summarizing and aggregating data, how to merge tables, loops, basic statistics, writing functions, and R scripts.

First, we need to set up our working environment. As in the Introduction to R course, we will set our working directory, load the tidyverse package, and source the prep_data.R script in order to load datasets for us to work with.

Review: tidy data and data transformation with dplyr

Tidy data

When working wtih a dataset, the shape of the data can be described by long form or wide form. In general, the preferred data format is long form data (also called tidy data), where each variable is in its own column, and each observation, or case, is in its own row. When data are organized this way, it is easy to access variables as vectors, or filter by categories.

We can use the gather() function to change wide form data to long form data, and spread() to change long form data to wide form data.

We currently have loaded a tibble called uscity that contains the population of for US cities in 2000 and 2010. By printing the data to screen, we can see that it is currently in long form, with each observation (city by year) having its own row, with the varaible (poplation), in a single column.

uscity_wide <- uscity %>%
  spread(key=Year, value=pop)

uscity_long <- uscity_wide %>%

Recall that two other useful functions in the tidy package are unite(), which can be used to combine two columns into one, and separate(), which can be used to split one column into two.

To demonstrate, let’s first combine the city and state columns into one, separated by “,”.

uscity_long <- uscity_long %>%
  unite(city, state, col="location", sep=", ", remove=TRUE)

Data Transformation

In Introduction to R, we also learned several functions to transform data matrices (tibbles) with dplyr. Here we will briefly review them.

The arrange() function can be used to reorder data. Let’s rearrange our uscity_long tibble so that the order matches the original uscity tibble.

uscity_long %>%
  arrange(city)
## # A tibble: 570 x 4
##           city state  Year     pop
##          <chr> <chr> <chr>   <dbl>
##  1     Abilene    TX  2000  115930
##  2     Abilene    TX  2010  117063
##  3       Akron    OH  2000  787289
##  4       Akron    OH  2010  199110
##  5 Albuquerque    NM  2000 1046798
##  6 Albuquerque    NM  2010  545852
##  7  Alexandria    VA  2000  128283
##  8  Alexandria    VA  2010  139966
##  9   Allentown    PA  2000  683040
## 10   Allentown    PA  2010  118032
## # ... with 560 more rows

By adding the desc() function to the arrange call, we can reverse the order.

uscity_long %>%
  arrange(desc(city))

The select() function can be used to select columns of the tibble, and can also be used to rename columns (remember the rename() fuction can also do this specifically). Keep in mind that you can select all columns, but in a different order, if you simply want to rearrange your columns.

For example, let’s rearrange the uscity_long columns, and rename pop to population and Year to year.

uscity_long %>%
  select(year = Year, state, city, population = pop)
## # A tibble: 570 x 4
##     year state        city population
##  * <chr> <chr>       <chr>      <dbl>

##  8  2000    AK   Anchorage     260283
##  9  2000    MI   Ann Arbor     397928
## 10  2000    CA     Antioch         NA

The distinct() function can be used to identify all unique values in a column. For example, we can find all of the unique values in the year column.

uscity_long %>%
  select(Year) %>%
  distinct()
## # A tibble: 2 x 1
##    Year
##   <chr>
## 1  2000
## 2  2010

Finally, the mutate() function can be used to create or update a column. Let’s round the pop colum to the nearest thousand.

uscity_long %>%
  mutate(pop = round(pop,digits = -3))

Review Exercises

Create a cleaned version of the housing dataset (called housing_clean). This will require a series of dplyr functions, chained together by pipes (%>%). We will work through each of these steps together to build our dataset. The steps are to:

  1. convert housing to a tibble

  2. convert to long form using gather, with location as the key and local_index as the value. Make sure to keep Date and National.US separate.

  3. convert location into state and city (remember, you need to do something to account for the extra space between city names). Be sure to remove the original location name

  4. convert date into year and month (remember, we don’t need the extra date)

  5. Rearrange the colums to be year, month, city, state, local_index and National.US (renamed national_index)

  6. arrange in order or year, month, state and finally city

  7. change year into an integer, use the month.abb vector to change the month integer to a name, change the city names to have “.” between the words to include “_“s instead (use the sub function), and finally, calculate a relative index (rel_index) by dividing the local_index by the national_index.

housing_clean <- housing %>% 
  as.tibble %>%
  gather(location, local_index, -Date, -National.US) %>% 
  separate(location, c("state", "city"),extra="merge") %>%
  separate(Date, c("year", "month"), extra="drop", remove=F) %>%
  select(year, month, city, state, local_index, national_index=National.US) %>%
  arrange(year, month, state, city) %>%
  mutate(year = as.integer(year), month = month.abb[as.integer(month)], city = sub(".", "_", city, fixed=TRUE), rel_index = local_index/national_index)

Filtering functions

The filter() function can be used to select rows meeting these conditions:

Summarzing and aggregating data

Once you have your data organized, you can use the summarize function in dplyr, along with the group_by helper function, to do a lot of powerful stuff.

We’ll continue to explore our mms dataset to demonstrate.

Okay, now what can we do with summarize? First, let’s just get the total number of M&Ms in this dataset:

mms %>% summarize(total_mms=sum(count))
## # A tibble: 1 x 1
##   total_mms
##       <int>
## 1      1713

The group_by function allows us to assign groups, which will then be “unwound” by summarize statements. Easiest to see by example:

mms %>%
  group_by(BagID) %>%
  summarize(mms_per_bag=sum(count)) %>% print %>% summarize(total_mms=sum(mms_per_bag))
## # A tibble: 30 x 2
##    BagID mms_per_bag
##    <int>       <int>
##  1     1          58
##  2     2          59
##  3     3          59
##  4     4          57
##  5     5          55
##  6     6          58
##  7     7          58
##  8     8          61
##  9     9          58
## 10    10          53
## # ... with 20 more rows
## # A tibble: 1 x 1
##   total_mms
##       <int>
## 1      1713

If we reverse the order of the group_by, the first table is the same (although sorted differently by default), but the second gives us totals by language, not province:

mms %>%
  group_by(color) %>%
  summarize(mms_per_color=sum(count)) %>% print %>% summarize(total_mms=sum(mms_per_color))
## # A tibble: 6 x 2
##    color mms_per_color
##    <chr>         <int>
## 1   Blue           217
## 2  Brown           374
## 3  Green           222
## 4 Orange           199
## 5    Red           288
## 6 Yellow           413
## # A tibble: 1 x 1
##   total_mms
##       <int>
## 1      1713

Note that summarize outputs a new tibble. You can continue to do calculations on this tibble (for example, if you data has many layers), but you cannot call your original tibble again within the same set of pipes.

We can do some tricky stuff with summarize, group_by, and mutate. For example, let’s get the fraction of each color in each bag:

mms %>%
  group_by(BagID) %>%
  mutate(percent = 100*(count/sum(count))) %>%
  select(-count) %>%
  spread(color, percent)
## # A tibble: 30 x 8
## # Groups:   BagID [30]

Note there is some subtle stuff going on here. When we us mutant on a grouped tibble, operations like sum() work within the grouping. So sum(count) computes the group-wise sum, which means it is easy to get frequencies or percents.

We can then use this insight to explore the data. For example, let’s get the 5 bags of M&Ms with the highest percentage of red candies, conditioning on a weight of at least 47g:

mms %>%
  group_by(BagID) %>%
  mutate(percent = 100*(count/sum(count))) %>%
  select(-count) %>%
  filter(color == "Red", Weight > 47) %>%
  arrange(desc(percent)) %>%
  head(n=5)
## # A tibble: 5 x 4
## # Groups:   BagID [5]
##   Weight BagID color  percent
##    <dbl> <int> <chr>    <dbl>
## 1  50.01    23   Red 35.71429
## 2  49.16     4   Red 26.31579
## 3  49.79     1   Red 25.86207
## 4  49.40    29   Red 25.86207
## 5  49.69    18   Red 24.13793

Note that we can send this to plotting functions like so:

mms %>%
  group_by(BagID) %>%
  mutate(percent = 100*(count/sum(count))) %>%
  select(-count) %>%
  filter(color == "Red", Weight > 47) %>%
  ggplot(aes(percent)) +
  geom_histogram(bins=15,fill="red")

Merging data

As a final data processing step, we’ll look at the merge functions in dplyr. These work kind of like sql queries, and take there names from the similar query syntax. All follow the pattern something_join. The most common are inner_join, left_join, right_join, and full_join, which keep rows with data in both dataframes, the left dataframe, the right dataframe, or either dataframe, respectively. We’ll look at a couple of examples, and then try a few exercises. Here, we’ll go back to the flights tibble, and use a dataset of US airport codes to add some additional information.

First, let’s just do a join to add the info from US airport codes to the flights dataset, merging on the destination airport.

flights2<-left_join(flights, us_aircodes, by=c("dest" = "iata_code")) %>% print

Statistics

Now let’s demonstrate a few statistical tests.

With our flights dataset, we might want to know if there is any difference between JFK and LGA in distance of flights. Let’s first make a quick boxplot to look at the data.

flights %>%
  filter(origin == "JFK" | origin == "LGA") %>%
  ggplot(aes(x=origin,y=distance)) +
  geom_boxplot()

Our boxplot suggests that flights that depart from JFK typically travel further distances than those that depart from LGA. Let’s test that using a T-test.

#note that we can use a logical test as a grouping variable in a formula
flights %>%
  filter(origin == "JFK" | origin == "LGA") %>%
  t.test(data=.,distance ~ origin)
## 
##  Welch Two Sample t-test
## 
## data:  distance by origin
## t = 166.49, df = 150360, p-value < 2.2e-16
## alternative hypothesis: true difference in means is not equal to 0
## 95 percent confidence interval:
##  480.6870 492.1398
## sample estimates:
## mean in group JFK mean in group LGA 
##         1266.2491          779.8357

We might want to do this non-parameterically using a Wilcoxon Rank Sum Test.

flights %>%
  filter(origin == "JFK" | origin == "LGA") %>%
  wilcox.test(data=.,distance ~ origin)
## 
##  Wilcoxon rank sum test with continuity correction
## 
## data:  distance by origin
## W = 7273100000, p-value < 2.2e-16
## alternative hypothesis: true location shift is not equal to 0

We might hypothesize that departure delay would be correlated with arrival delay. Let’s test that with cor.test(), and then plot it to see if our hunch might be correct.

cor.test(flights$dep_delay, flights$arr_delay)

Let’s say we want to find out whether or not there is any difference in the proportion of delayed flights among the three airports, where we are only concerned whether a flight is delayed (departure delay) or on time, rather than how delayed a flight is. What would you do?

First, we need to create a new column in our dataframe, categorizing flights as delayed or not (1 = delayed, 0 = ontime). Hint: use mutate() and ifelse().

flights <- flights %>%

Next, let’s get a sense of how many flights have a departure delay in the dataset, grouped by origin.

Loops and Conditional Statements

For Loops

Sometimes you will have a vector, object, or list of objects, where you will want to perform the same series of actions on each member of an object. For this, we can use a for loop.

For example, let’s create an R object type we have not yet used, a list. A list is similar to a vector, but the objects of a list do not have to be of the same type. For example, let’s create three numeric vectors with 5 different numbers in each, and then use the list() function to group them into a list.

vec1 <- c(1, 5, 2, 6, 9)
vec2 <- c(17, 4, 6, 81, 34)
vec3 <- c(17, 34, 62, 5, 1)

list1 <- list(vec1,vec2,vec3)

If you look at list1, you can see all three vectors, and notice that you can subset them with [[]]. For example, to pull the third object in the list, you would use list1[[3]].

list1[[3]]
## [1] 17 34 62  5  1

Now, we are going to use a for loop to iterate through this list and calculate the mean of each list. Everything in between the brackets of the for loop will be performed before moving on to the next item in the list.

for (vec in list1){
  print(mean(vec))
}  
## [1] 4.6
## [1] 28.4
## [1] 23.8

Note that this is useful, but sometimes rather than iterating through the objects themselves, it is useful to iterate through a vector of numbers, so you can still access each item, but save the results to a new vector. For example:

#Create a new empty vector
mean_vec <- vector()

for (i in 1:length(list1)){
  mean_vec[i] <- mean(list1[[i]])
}

mean_vec
## [1]  4.6 28.4 23.8

You see that we use i to stand in for the number in the sequence. It is also always better to calculate the numbers to iterate through based on the length of you object, rather than hard coding (e.g. 1:3). That way if you update your object later, you don’t have to worry about changing your for loop.

If Statements

If statements (also known as flow control) are also useful, particularly when working with for loops or writing functions (as you will see below). Similar to the ifelse() function we used above, we will write a statement where if (something is true) {do everything in the brackets} else {do something else}.

Perhaps it is easier to explain by example. Let’s create a vec4 that is 6 elements long to demonstrate, and create a new list containing these four vectors. Let’s then pass it to an if else statement that prints one thing if the vector has a length <= 5, and something else otherwise.

vec4 <- c(1, 5, 3, 9, 1, 9, 3)

list2 <- list(vec1,vec2,vec3,vec4)

for (vec in list2){
  if (length(vec) <= 5){
    print("This vector is no longer than 5 elements")
  }
  else {
    print("This vector is longer than 5 elements")
  }
}
## [1] "This vector is no longer than 5 elements"
## [1] "This vector is no longer than 5 elements"
## [1] "This vector is no longer than 5 elements"
## [1] "This vector is longer than 5 elements"

Functions

Tidy data is of course extremely useful. But in order to take full advantage of nicely organized data, you will often need to write your own functions to operate on it.

Simply put, custom functions are easy ways to package your code for reuse. If you find that you are running a specific set of analysis steps on many data subsets, or many files, it is cleaner and easier to maintain if you move the analysis to a set of functions that can be run with input.

It is easy to find the code for the functions you use - just type the name of the functions without parentheses:

ls

To get started writing custom functions, we’ll do some very simple things. For example, R has no built in function to calculate the geometric mean of a vector of numbers. We can write one, like this:

geoMean <- function(x) {
  prod(x)^(1/length(x))
}

test_vec = rnorm(100,5,2)
geoMean(test_vec)
## [1] 4.561687

Just like data, we are assigning the funtion to an object, geoMean. We can then call the geoMean function just like built in R functions, e.g. mean(). Note that unlike mean (which has a trim option and an na.rm option), we currently don’t have any options besides the required option x, a numeric vector.

Functions Exercise 1:

Write a simple function to calculate the standard deviation of a vector. It should take one required input, a vector, and return the square root of the variance, which you can compute using the sqrt and var functions.

Try running it on test_vec, you should get something close to 2

## [1] 1.808738

We can add additional options, say to control how missing data is handled. E.g., let’s add the removeNA option, with a default of TRUE, to our geoMean function.

geoMean <- function(x, removeNA=TRUE) {
  if (removeNA) {
    y=x[!is.na(x)]
    prod(y)^(1/length(y))
  } else {
    prod(x)^(1/length(x))
  }
}

test_vec2 = c(test_vec,NA)
geoMean(test_vec)
## [1] 4.561687
geoMean(test_vec2)
## [1] 4.561687
geoMean(test_vec2, removeNA=FALSE)
## [1] NA

Functions Exercise 2

Rewrite your stDev() function to include a removeNA option with the default being FALSE

Note that we use if {} else {} for flow control here. Flow control options like this are rarely useful in R outside of functions, but can be quite useful inside them, especially to make options work.

You can also nest functions. A function created instead another function will be available in the function, but not outside the function.

allMeans <- function(x, method="arithmetic", removeNA=TRUE) {
  harmMean <- function(x, removeNA=TRUE) {
    if (removeNA) {
      y=x[!is.na(x)]
      length(y)/sum(1/y)
    } else {
      length(x)/sum(1/x)
    }
  }

  means<-list()
  means[['arithmetic']] = mean(x, na.rm=removeNA)
  means[['harmonic']] = harmMean(x, removeNA=removeNA)
  means[['geometic']] = geoMean(x, removeNA=removeNA)
  
  if ("all" %in% c(method)) {
    return(means)
  }
  else {
    return(means[method])
  }
}

We can’t use harmMean without going through allMeans. Try it, you’ll get an error.

This, of course, just scratches the surface of where the combination of tidy data and turning your analysis into functions can go. As a final example, let’s make a custom function that will take aclassification variable, a numeric variable, and a number of permutations, and compute a p-value by permutation (this is not very sophisticated, so don’t use this in production code, it is just an example). We’ll use the flights data as a model.

permutation_p <- function(DF, value, key, test_elem, alpha=0.05, nperm=100) {
  #good idea to make a comment that reminds you what each argument does
  #DF = data frame to operate on
  #value = column of data frame that is the numeric value to test
  #key = column of data frame containing categorical variable
  #test_elem = element we want to compare to others to as whether it is greater or less than
  #alpha = p-value cutoff to compute; we'll report if the test is significant at this threshold
  #nperm = # of permutations
  
  #function to compute means
  meandiff_perm <- function(v1,v2) {
    v2<-sample(v2)
    mean(v1[v2], na.rm=TRUE) - mean(v1[!v2], na.rm=TRUE)
  }
  
  repeat_meandiff<-function(n, v1, v2) {
    replicate(n, meandiff_perm(v1=v1, v2=v2))
  }
  
  v1<-unlist(DF[value])
  v2<-unlist(DF[key]==test_elem)
  realtest = mean(v1[v2], na.rm=TRUE) - mean(v1[!v2], na.rm=TRUE)
  perm_res<-repeat_meandiff(nperm, v1=v1, v2=v2)
  dir = sign(realtest)
  sig = mean(abs(realtest) < abs(perm_res))
  if(sig <= alpha) {
    if(dir < 0) {
      return("down")
    } else {
      return("up")
    } 
  } else {
    return("ns")
  }
}

permutation_p(flights, "air_time", "carrier", "HA", nperm=100)
## [1] "up"

It isn’t fast, but you can hopefully see how elaborate this can get. Now we can do something like run this test across different months.

flights %>% group_by(month) %>% 
  summarize(AlaskaAir_flighttime_diff = permutation_p(., "air_time", "carrier", "AS", nperm=100))

R Scripts

Today we have been workign within an R script. These are crucial to use when working in R, because it is documentation of the analyses you ran. When you are working on this project later, you can go back and replicate your analyses, tweak them, or share this with others to reproduce your work.

Sometimes, it is also useful to create R scripts with a set of tasks you want to automate. If you save these tasks in a script, you can either put them on Odyssey to run on the cluster, or execute everything in them. Let’s create a new quick script as an example.

Create a new “test_script.R” with the following: setwd(“~/Dropbox/Informatics/Workshops/”) x <- 1:5 y <- c(5,1,4,11,8) pdf(“test_plot2.pdf”) plot(y ~ x) dev.off()

Save that script, and now you can run it by typing:

#source("test_script.R")

Exercise: write a script to generate a plot of the flights data from scratch

  1. decide what you want to plot. Anything you want, but has to include at least one column not in the default bus dataset or a subset of the default bus dataset
  2. load in the data
  3. make required modifications 2b. change the working directory to a new directory that will have the output (has to already exist on your computer)
  4. open a pdf device to a file
  5. make your plot
  6. close pdf device with dev.off()

To really test your script, you can clear your workspace before running!
